{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539791"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16703"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16703"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.1,0.38,0.28,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108159"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9394"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90571"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11097"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43641"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108159"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for advice regarding HIV transmission risk. She has been living with HIV for five years and has been on antiretroviral therapy. She has maintained an undetectable viral load (less than 200 copies/mL) for the past two years with excellent medication adherence. She has recently started dating and wants to discuss safe sex practices with her HIV-negative partner. Her only other medical condition is mild asthma, for which she uses a salbutamol inhaler as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her most recent results from two weeks ago show CD4 count 850 cells/\u00b5L (500-1500) and HIV viral load less than 20 copies/mL.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes her risk of sexually transmitting HIV to her partner?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High risk requiring multiple prevention strategies","Moderate risk requiring condom use","Low risk with regular viral load monitoring","No risk of transmission","Low risk if partner takes pre-exposure prophylaxis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario addresses the concept of Undetectable = Untransmittable (U=U), which is supported by robust scientific evidence. The patient has maintained an undetectable viral load (less than 200 copies/mL) for two years, which means there is effectively no risk of sexual HIV transmission to her partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo risk of transmission\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer, based on multiple large-scale studies including PARTNER and HPTN 052, which found zero linked HIV transmissions from people with sustained undetectable viral loads to their HIV-negative partners, even with condomless sex. The evidence for U=U has transformed HIV prevention and helped reduce stigma associated with HIV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh risk requiring multiple prevention strategies\u003C/strong\u003E significantly overstates the risk and could perpetuate unnecessary stigma and anxiety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModerate risk requiring condom use\u003C/strong\u003E implies that condoms are necessary to prevent transmission, which is incorrect when viral load is undetectable. While condoms protect against other sexually transmitted infections, they are not required to prevent HIV transmission in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow risk with regular viral load monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E understates the evidence - the risk is effectively zero, not low, when viral load is undetectable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow risk if partner takes pre-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because PrEP is not necessary when the HIV-positive partner maintains an undetectable viral load.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that maintaining an undetectable status requires continued adherence to antiretroviral therapy and regular monitoring of viral load. Confirmation of antiretroviral therapy adherence typically requires at least two consecutive undetectable viral load results separated by a minimum of four weeks, though some clinicians prefer a more conservative approach of a full 6-month period with consistently undetectable results. For patients on a stable, suppressive antiretroviral regimen, viral load monitoring should occur every 3-4 months initially. For patients who demonstrate consistent adherence with suppressed viral loads for over a year and stable clinical and immunological status, this interval may be extended to every 6 months. Regular monitoring remains essential to ensure continued effectiveness of treatment and prevention. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An undetectable HIV viral load means there is effectively no risk of sexual transmission to HIV-negative partners.","Regular viral load monitoring and medication adherence are essential for maintaining undetectable status.","Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is not required for HIV-negative partners when the HIV-positive partner maintains an undetectable viral load."],"references":["Australian STI Management Guidelines. HIV [Internet]. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: http://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/hiv/","Rodger AJ, Cambiano V, Bruun T, Vernazza P, Collins S, Degen O, Corbelli GM, Estrada V, Geretti AM, Beloukas A, Raben D, Coll P, Antinori A, Nwokolo N, Rieger A, Prins JM, Blaxhult A, Weber R, Van Eeden A, Brockmeyer NH, Clarke A, Del Romero Guerrero J, Raffi F, Bogner JR, Wandeler G, Gerstoft J, Guti\u00e9rrez F, Brinkman K, Kitchen M, Ostergaard L, Leon A, Ristola M, Jessen H, Stellbrink HJ, Phillips AN, Lundgren J; PARTNER Study Group. Risk of HIV transmission through condomless sex in serodifferent gay couples with the HIV-positive partner taking suppressive antiretroviral therapy (PARTNER): final results of a multicentre, prospective, observational study. Lancet. 2019 Jun 15;393(10189):2428-2438. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30418-0. Epub 2019 May 2. PMID: 31056293; PMCID: PMC6584382.","The Australasian Society of HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine (2020). U=U ASHM Guidance for Healthcare Professionals (3rd Edition) Allan. B (Ed.) October 2020","Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine (ASHM). Plasma HIV-1 RNA (Viral Load) and CD4 Count Monitoring. HIV Management Guidelines. Sydney: ASHM; 2023 Jul. Available from: https://hiv.guidelines.org.au/arv-adult/testing/count-monitoring/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90571"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16703"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90571"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-07T10:56:28+09:30","updatedAt":"20